# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: anglo-scottish-border
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:anglo-scottish-border/10th-century] The **10th century** was the period from 901 (represented by the Roman numerals CMI) through 1000 (M) in accordance with the Julian calendar, and the last century of the 1st millennium.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/10th-century] In China, the Song dynasty was established, with most of China reuniting after the fall of the Tang dynasty and the following Five Dynasties and Ten Kingdoms period.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/10th-century] Vietnam finally achieves independence from Chinese dominion as a result.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/10th-century] The Muslim World experienced a cultural zenith, especially in al-Andalus under the Caliphate of Córdoba and in the Samanid Empire under Ismail Samani.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/10th-century] The Abbasid Caliphate continued to exist but with reduced central authority.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/10th-century] Additionally, there was a cultural flourishing for the Byzantine Empire, which also reconquered some lost territories, and the First Bulgarian Empire, as well as the Holy Roman Empire during the Ottonian Renaissance.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/10th-century] The historian Lynn White mentions of the period that "to the modern eye, it is very nearly the darkest of the Dark Ages ... if it was dark, it was the darkness of the womb".
[src:anglo-scottish-border/10th-century] Caesar Baronius described it as the Iron Century, because it was 'iron in its harshness and in its sterility of goodness', while Lorenzo Valla gave it the similar name "Age of Lead and Iron".
[src:anglo-scottish-border/1983-france-united-kingdom-maritime-boundary-convention] The **1983 France – United Kingdom Maritime Boundary Convention** is a 1983 treaty between France and the United Kingdom which establishes the maritime boundary between French Polynesia and the British territory of the Pitcairn Islands.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/1983-france-united-kingdom-maritime-boundary-convention] The treaty was signed in Paris on 25 October 1983.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/1983-france-united-kingdom-maritime-boundary-convention] The text of the treaty sets out a boundary that is an equidistant line between the nearest islands of the two territories.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/1983-france-united-kingdom-maritime-boundary-convention] The boundary is roughly north–south and consists of five straight-line maritime segments defined by six individual coordinate points.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/1983-france-united-kingdom-maritime-boundary-convention] The convention came into force on 12 April 1984, after both states had ratified it.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/1983-france-united-kingdom-maritime-boundary-convention] In 1993, after the United Kingdom declared an Exclusive Economic Zone (EEZ) around the Pitcairn Islands, the two states agreed that the boundary set out in the 1983 treaty should also be the boundary between the French and British EEZs in the South Pacific.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/1983-france-united-kingdom-maritime-boundary-convention] The full name of the treaty is *Convention on Maritime Boundaries between the Government of the French Republic and the Government of the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Northern Ireland*.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/1993-united-kingdom-united-states-maritime-boundary-treaties] The **1993 United Kingdom–United States Maritime Boundary Treaties** are two treaties between the United Kingdom and the United States which established a maritime boundary between British territories and American territories in the Caribbean Sea.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/1993-united-kingdom-united-states-maritime-boundary-treaties] Both treaties were signed in London on 5 November 1993.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/1993-united-kingdom-united-states-maritime-boundary-treaties] The first treaty delimits the boundary between the British territory of Anguilla and the United States Virgin Islands.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/1993-united-kingdom-united-states-maritime-boundary-treaties] The boundary is a simplified equidistant line that consists of a single maritime straight-line segment 1.34 nautical miles (2.48 km; 1.54 mi) long.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/1993-united-kingdom-united-states-maritime-boundary-treaties] It is defined by a straight line connecting two individual coordinate points.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/1993-united-kingdom-united-states-maritime-boundary-treaties] The full name of the treaty is *Treaty between the Government of the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Northern Ireland and the Government of the United States of America on the Delimitation in the Caribbean of a Maritime Boundary between the US Virgin Islands and Anguilla*.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/1993-united-kingdom-united-states-maritime-boundary-treaties] The second treaty delimits the boundary between the British Virgin Islands and the United States Virgin Islands and Puerto Rico.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/1993-united-kingdom-united-states-maritime-boundary-treaties] The boundary is a simplified equidistant line that runs in a south–south-east direction until it terminates at the tripoint of Anguilla.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/1993-united-kingdom-united-states-maritime-boundary-treaties] It is far longer and more complicated than the Anguilla–U.S.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/1993-united-kingdom-united-states-maritime-boundary-treaties] Virgin Islands boundary: it is about 200 nautical miles (370 km; 230 mi) long and consists of 49 straight-line segments defined by 50 individual coordinate points.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/1993-united-kingdom-united-states-maritime-boundary-treaties] The two treaties entered into force on 1 June 1995 after they had been ratified by both states.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/1996-france-united-kingdom-maritime-delimitation-agreements] The **1996 France – United Kingdom Maritime Delimitation Agreements** are two treaties between France and the United Kingdom which establish a number of maritime boundary between French territories and British territories in the Caribbean Sea.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/1996-france-united-kingdom-maritime-delimitation-agreements] Both treaties were signed in London on 27 June 1996.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/1996-france-united-kingdom-maritime-delimitation-agreements] The two treaties entered into force on 30 January 1997 after they had been ratified by both states.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/1996-france-united-kingdom-maritime-delimitation-agreements] The first treaty delimits the boundary in the Anguilla Channel between the British territory of Anguilla and the French territories of Saint Martin and Saint Barthélemy.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/1996-france-united-kingdom-maritime-delimitation-agreements] The boundary is a simplified equidistant maritime line that runs in roughly an east–west direction.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/1996-france-united-kingdom-maritime-delimitation-agreements] It consists of seven straight-line segments defined by eight individual coordinate points.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/1996-france-united-kingdom-maritime-delimitation-agreements] The western end of the border forms a tripoint with the Netherlands Antilles and the easternmost end of the border forms the tripoint with Antigua and Barbuda.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/1996-france-united-kingdom-maritime-delimitation-agreements] The full name of the treaty is *Agreement on maritime delimitation between the Government of the French Republic and the Government of the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Northern Ireland concerning Saint Martin and Saint Barthélemy, on one hand, and Anguilla on the other*.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/1996-france-united-kingdom-maritime-delimitation-agreements] When the treaty was signed, Saint Martin and Saint Barthélemy were both part of the Guadeloupe overseas department of France.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/1996-france-united-kingdom-maritime-delimitation-agreements] In 2007, Saint Martin and Saint Barthélemy became two separate overseas collectivities of France.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/1996-france-united-kingdom-maritime-delimitation-agreements] As a result, the first treaty now defines only the Anguilla – Saint Martin maritime boundary.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/1996-france-united-kingdom-maritime-delimitation-agreements] There is no maritime boundary between Anguilla and the separate collectivity of Saint Barthélemy.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/1996-france-united-kingdom-maritime-delimitation-agreements] The second treaty delimits the boundary between the British territory of Montserrat and the French territory of Guadeloupe.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/1996-france-united-kingdom-maritime-delimitation-agreements] The boundary is a simplified equidistant line that runs through the Guadeloupe Passage in roughly an east–west direction.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/1996-france-united-kingdom-maritime-delimitation-agreements] It consists of four straight-line segments defined by five individual coordinate points.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/1996-france-united-kingdom-maritime-delimitation-agreements] The western end of the border forms the tripoint with Venezuela and the easternmost end of the border forms a tripoint with Antigua and Barbuda.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/1996-france-united-kingdom-maritime-delimitation-agreements] The full name of the treaty is *Agreement on maritime delimitation between the Government of the French Republic and the Government of the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Northern Ireland concerning Guadeloupe and Montserrat*.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/2001-uk-census] A nationwide census, known as **Census 2001**, was conducted in the United Kingdom on Sunday, 29 April 2001.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/2001-uk-census] This was the 20th UK census and recorded a resident population of 58,789,194.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/2001-uk-census] The 2001 UK census was organised by the Office for National Statistics (ONS) in England and Wales, the General Register Office for Scotland (GROS) and the Northern Ireland Statistics and Research Agency (NISRA).
[src:anglo-scottish-border/2001-uk-census] Detailed results by region, council area, ward and output area are available from their respective websites.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/2001-uk-census] Similar to previous UK censuses, the 2001 census was organised by the three statistical agencies, ONS, GROS, and NISRA, and coordinated at the national level by the Office for National Statistics.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/2001-uk-census] The Orders in Council to conduct the census, specifying the people and information to be included in the census, were made under the authority of the Census Act 1920 in Great Britain, and the Census Act (Northern Ireland) 1969 in Northern Ireland.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/2001-uk-census] In England and Wales these regulations were made by the Census Order 2000 (SI 744/2000), in Scotland by the Census (Scotland) Order 2000 (SSI 68/2000), and in Northern Ireland by the Census Order (Northern Ireland) 2000 (SRNI 168/2000).
[src:anglo-scottish-border/2001-uk-census] The census was administered through self-completion forms, in most cases delivered by enumerators to households and communal establishments in the three weeks before census night on 29 April.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/2001-uk-census] For the first time return by post was used as the main collection method, with enumerators following up in person where the forms were not returned.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/2001-uk-census] The postal response rate was 88% in England and Wales, 91% in Scotland, and 92% in Northern Ireland.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/2001-uk-census] A total of 81,000 field staff were employed across the UK (70,000 in England and Wales, 8,000 in Scotland and 3,000 in Northern Ireland).
[src:anglo-scottish-border/2001-uk-census] The census was conducted at the height of the foot-and-mouth crisis, which led to extra precautions being adopted by the field staff, and suggestions that the census may have to be postponed.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/2001-uk-census] However, it was reported that the disease outbreak did not affect the effectiveness of the collection process.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/2001-uk-census] The census was estimated to cost £259m over its 13-year cycle from the start of planning in 1993 to the delivery of final results in 2006.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/2001-uk-census] Printing of the 30 million census forms was subcontracted to Polestar Group, and processing of the returned census forms was subcontracted to Lockheed Martin in a contract worth £54m.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/2001-uk-census] The forms were initially scanned into digital format, then read with OMR and OCR, with manual entry where the automatic process could not read the forms.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/2001-uk-census] The forms were then pulped and recycled, and the digital copies printed onto microfilm for storage and release after 100 years.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/2001-uk-census] Once the data were returned to the statistics agencies it underwent further processing to ensure consistency and to impute missing values.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/2001-uk-census] The overall response rate for the census, that is the proportion of the population who were included on a census form, was estimated to be 94% in England and Wales, 96.1% in Scotland and 95.2% in Northern Ireland.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/2001-uk-census] This was due to a number of factors: households with no response, households excluding residents from their returns, and addresses not included in the enumeration.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/2001-uk-census] In Manchester for example 25,000 people from 14,000 addresses were not enumerated because the address database was two years out of date.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/2001-uk-census] The Local Authority with the lowest response was Kensington and Chelsea with 64%.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/2001-uk-census] Hackney had the next lowest response at 72%.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/2001-uk-census] Out of all local authorities, the ten lowest response rates were all in London.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/2001-uk-census] The results still represent 100 per cent of the population, however, because some individuals not completing their forms were instead identified by census enumerators, and through the use of cross-matching with a follow-up survey.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/2001-uk-census] The results from the 2001 census were produced using a methodology known as the One Number Census.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/2001-uk-census] This was an attempt to adjust the census counts and impute answers to allow for estimated under-enumeration measured by the Census Coverage Survey (sample size 320,000 households), resulting in a single set of population estimates.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/2001-uk-census] Although the 1851 census had included a question about religion on a separate response sheet, whose completion was not compulsory, the 2001 census was the first in Great Britain to ask about the religion of respondents on the main census form.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/2001-uk-census] An amendment to the 1920 Census Act (the Census (Amendment) Act 2000) was passed by Parliament to allow the question to be asked, and to allow the response to this question to be optional.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/2001-uk-census] The inclusion of the question enabled the Jedi census phenomenon to take place in the United Kingdom.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/2001-uk-census] In England and Wales 390,127 people stated their religion as Jedi, as did 14,052 people in Scotland.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/2001-uk-census] 15% declared themselves of no religion (including Jedi at 0.7%, more than those who declared themselves as Sikh, Jewish or Buddhist) and 8% did not respond to the question.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/2001-uk-census] Since the UK census relies on self-completion, the composition of the other ethnic group category is not fixed.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/2001-uk-census] Analysis by the Office for National Statistics of the 220,000 people in England and Wales who ticked the other ethnic group box in the 2001 census reveals that 53 per cent were born in the Far East, 10 per cent in the UK, 10 per cent in the Middle East, and 7 per cent in Africa.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/2001-uk-census] People could write in an ethnic group under the 'other' heading.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/2001-uk-census] 26 per cent did not specify an ethnicity, but of the remainder 23 per cent wrote Filipino, 21 per cent Japanese, 11 per cent Vietnamese, 11 per cent Arab, 6 per cent Middle Eastern and 4 per cent North African.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/2001-uk-census] Controversy surrounding the classification of ethnic groups began as early as 2000, when it was revealed that respondents in Scotland and Northern Ireland would be able to check a box describing themselves as Scottish or Irish, an option not available for English respondents.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/2001-uk-census] With an absence of an English tick-box, the only other tickbox available was "white-British", "Irish", or "other".
[src:anglo-scottish-border/2001-uk-census] However, if 'English' was written in under the "any other white background" it was not clear whether it would be counted as an ethnic group in same the way as the Welsh.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/2001-uk-census] Following criticism, English was included as a tick-box option in the 2011 census.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/2001-uk-census] It is sometimes claimed that the 2001 census revealed that two-thirds of the population of Wales described themselves as of Welsh nationality.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/2001-uk-census] In fact, the 2001 census did not collect any information on nationality.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/2001-uk-census] Controversy surrounding the classification of ethnic group began as early as 2000, when it was revealed that respondents in Scotland and Northern Ireland would be able to check a box describing themselves as Scottish or Irish, an option not available for Welsh respondents.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/2001-uk-census] Prior to the census, *Plaid Cymru* backed a petition calling for the inclusion of a Welsh tickbox and for the National Assembly for Wales to have primary law-making powers and its own National Statistics Office.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/2001-uk-census] With an absence of a Welsh tickbox, the only other tickbox available was "white-British", "Irish", or "other".
[src:anglo-scottish-border/2001-uk-census] For the first time in a UK census, those wishing to describe their ethnicity as Cornish were given their own code number (06) on the 2001 UK census form, alongside those for people wishing to describe themselves as English, Welsh, Irish or Scottish.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/2001-uk-census] About 34,000 people in Cornwall and 3,500 people in the rest of the UK wrote on their census forms in 2001 that they considered their ethnic group to be Cornish.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/2001-uk-census] This represented nearly 7% of the population of Cornwall.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/2001-uk-census] Various Cornish organisations were campaigning for the inclusion of the Cornish tick box on the next census in 2011.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/a7-road-great-britain] The **A7** is a major road, partly a trunk road, that connects Edinburgh in Central Scotland to Carlisle in North West England.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/a7-road-great-britain] The A7 meets the M6 motorway close to Carlisle, which connects to the English motorway network.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/a7-road-great-britain] The northern terminus of the A7 is the junction at North Bridge with Princes Street in Edinburgh, also the northern terminus of the A1 and the southern terminus of the A900.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/a7-road-great-britain] The road passes Cameron Toll, before meeting the Edinburgh City Bypass at the Sheriffhall Roundabout.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/a7-road-great-britain] South of the bypass, the A7 continues through Midlothian past Newtongrange and Gorebridge.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/a7-road-great-britain] Continuing from Midlothian into the Scottish Borders, the road bypasses Heriot then passes through Stow to reach Galashiels.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/a7-road-great-britain] The A7 becomes a trunk road at the southern boundary of Galashiels.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/a7-road-great-britain] It continues south to Selkirk; a bypass here has been proposed for years but not implemented.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/a7-road-great-britain] This section of the A7 runs parallel to the Borders Railway which opened in 2015; Network Rail and MPs met during construction to mitigate the effect of works traffic on the road.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/a7-road-great-britain] In Hawick the A7 continues along the north bank of the River Teviot to cross the river at the Albert Bridge and follows the south bank of the river towards Langholm, then bypasses Canonbie.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/a7-road-great-britain] South of Langholm the road has been improved, allowing for overtaking.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/a7-road-great-britain] Continuing across the English border, the A7 goes through Longtown, before meeting the A689 and the M6 at the Greymoorhill Roundabout.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/a7-road-great-britain] The A7 becomes a dual carriageway close to the Kingstown Industrial Estate on the northern fringe of Carlisle.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/a7-road-great-britain] Continuing as a single carriageway road, the A7 crosses the River Eden over Eden Bridge.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/a7-road-great-britain] At Hardwicke Circus Roundabout in the centre of Carlisle, the A7 meets the A595 to the west and southern Cumbria, then continues to form part of Carlisle's one way system through the city centre, meeting the A69 and finally becoming the A6 near Carlisle railway station.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/a7-road-great-britain] The English section was detrunked in 2005.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/a7-road-great-britain] In the late 1970s, the A7 was described as being slow and tortuous.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/a7-road-great-britain] It was the 28th most dangerous UK road in 2017.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/a7-road-great-britain] The A7 Action Group was founded in 1990, and continues to lobby for safety improvements to the road, including a bypass of Selkirk.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/a7-road-great-britain] Note: Junctions are listed northbound from Carlisle to Edinburgh.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] The **Acts of Union** refer to two acts of Parliament, one by the Parliament of Scotland in March 1707, followed shortly thereafter by an equivalent act of the Parliament of England.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] They put into effect the international Treaty of Union agreed on 22 July 1706, which politically joined the Kingdom of England and Kingdom of Scotland into a single "political state" named Great Britain, with Queen Anne as its sovereign.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] The English and Scottish acts of ratification took effect on 1 May 1707, creating the new kingdom, with its parliament based in the Palace of Westminster.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] The two countries had shared a monarch since the "personal" Union of the Crowns in 1603, when James VI of Scotland inherited the English throne from his cousin Elizabeth I to become (in addition) 'James I of England', styled James VI and I.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] Prior to 1603, England and Scotland had different monarchs, but when Elizabeth I died without children, she was succeeded as King of England by her distant relative, James VI of Scotland.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] After her death, the two Crowns were held in personal union by James (reigning as James VI and I), who announced his intention to unite the two realms.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] The 1603 Union of England and Scotland Act established a joint Commission to agree terms, but the Parliament of England was concerned this would lead to an absolutist structure similar to that of Scotland.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] James was forced to withdraw his proposals, but used the royal prerogative to take the title "King of Great Britain".
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] Attempts to revive the project of union in 1610 were met with hostility.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] English opponents such as Sir Edwin Sandys argued that changing the name of England "were as yf [*sic*] to make a conquest of our name, which was more than ever the Dane or Norman could do".
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] Instead, James set about creating a unified Church of Scotland and England, as the first step towards a centralised, Unionist state.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] However, despite both being nominally Episcopal in structure, the two were very different in doctrine; the Church of Scotland, or kirk, was Calvinist in doctrine, and viewed many Church of England practices as little better than Catholicism.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] As a result, attempts to impose religious policy by James and his son Charles I ultimately led to the 1639–1651 Wars of the Three Kingdoms.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] The 1639–1640 Bishops' Wars confirmed the primacy of the Scots kirk, and established a Covenanter government in Scotland.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] The Scots remained neutral when the First English Civil War began in 1642, before becoming concerned at the impact on Scotland of an English Royalist victory.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] Presbyterian leaders like Argyll viewed union as a way to ensure free trade between England and Scotland, and preserve a Scots Presbyterian kirk.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] Under the 1643 Solemn League and Covenant, the Scots Parliament agreed to provide military support to its English counterpart in return for a united Presbyterian church, but did not explicitly commit to political union.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] As the war progressed, Scots and English Presbyterians increasingly viewed the English Independents, and associated radical groups like the Levellers, as a bigger threat than the Royalists.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] Both Royalists and Presbyterians agreed monarchy was divinely ordered, but disagreed on the nature and extent of Royal authority over the church.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] When Charles I surrendered in 1646, an English pro-Royalist faction known as the Engagers allied with their former enemies to restore him to the English throne.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] After defeat in the 1647–1648 Second English Civil War, Scotland was occupied by English troops, which were withdrawn once those whom Cromwell held responsible had been replaced by the Kirk Party.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] In December 1648, Pride's Purge paved the way for the Trial of Charles I in England by excluding MPs who opposed it.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] Following the execution of Charles I in January 1649, and establishment of the Commonwealth of England, the Scots Kirk Party proclaimed Charles II King of Scots and England and, in the 1650 Treaty of Breda, resolved to restore him to the English throne.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] Instead, defeat in the Anglo-Scottish War resulted in Scotland's incorporation into the Commonwealth in 1653, largely driven by Cromwell's determination to break the power of the Scots kirk.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] The 1652 Tender of Union was followed on 12 April 1654 by *An Ordinance by the Protector for the Union of England and Scotland,* creating the Commonwealth of England and Scotland.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] It was ratified by the Second Protectorate Parliament on 26 June 1657, creating a single Parliament in Westminster, with 30 representatives each from Scotland and Ireland added to the existing English members.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] While integration into the Commonwealth established free trade between Scotland and England, the economic benefits were diminished by the costs of military occupation.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] Both Scotland and England associated union with heavy taxes and military rule; it had little popular support in either Country, and the union was dissolved after the Restoration of Charles II in 1660.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] The Scottish economy was badly damaged by the (protectionist) English Navigation Acts of 1660 and 1663 and England's wars with the Dutch Republic, Scotland's major export market.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] An Anglo-Scots Trade Commission was set up in January 1668 but the English had no interest in making concessions, as the Scots had little to offer in return.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] In 1669, Charles II revived talks on "political union"; his motives may have been to weaken Scotland's commercial and political links with the Dutch, still seen as an enemy and complete the work of his grandfather James I and VI.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] On the Scottish side, the proposed union received parliamentary support, boosted by the desire to ensure free trade.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] Continued opposition meant these negotiations were abandoned by the end of 1669.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] The Convention of the Estates issued an address to William and Mary "as both kingdomes are united in one head and soveraigne so they may become one body pollitick, one nation to be represented in one parliament", reserving "our church government, as it shall be established at the tyme of the union".
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] William and Mary were supportive of the idea but it was opposed both by the Presbyterian majority in Scotland and the English Parliament.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] Episcopacy in Scotland was abolished in 1690, alienating a significant part of the political class; it was this element that later formed the bedrock of opposition to Union.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] The 1690s were a time of economic hardship in Europe as a whole and Scotland in particular, a period now known as the Seven ill years which led to strained relations with England.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] In 1698, the Company of Scotland Trading to Africa and the Indies received a charter to raise capital through public subscription.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] The Company invested in the Darién scheme, an ambitious plan funded almost entirely by Scottish investors to build a colony on the Isthmus of Panama for trade with East Asia.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] The scheme was a disaster; the losses of over £150,000 severely impacted the Scottish commercial system.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] The International Treaty, and English and Scots acts of ratification of Union may be seen within a wider European context of increasing state centralisation during the late 17th and early 18th centuries, including the monarchies of France, Sweden, Denmark-Norway and Spain.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] While there were exceptions, such as the Dutch Republic or the Republic of Venice, the trend was clear.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] The dangers of the monarch using one parliament against the other first became apparent in 1647 and 1651.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] It resurfaced during the 1679 to 1681 Exclusion Crisis, caused by English resistance to the Catholic prince James (later James II of England, James VII of Scots) succeeding his brother Charles II.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] It then went beyond ensuring James's succession to the Scots throne by explicitly stating the aim was to make his exclusion from the English throne impossible without "the fatall and dreadfull consequences of a civil war".
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] The issue reappeared during the 1688 Dutch invasion and *coup d'etat* (subsequently entitled as "the Glorious Revolution").
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] The English Convention Parliament generally supported replacing James with his Protestant daughter Mary, holding to their "legal fiction" that James, by fleeing to France, had abandoned his English subjects and "abdicated".
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] They initially resisted making her Dutch husband William of Orange joint ruler but relented, "fearing the return of James" only when William threatened to take his troops and fleet and return to the Netherlands, and Mary refused to rule without him.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] In Scotland, it became a Constitutional issue.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] The fact that King James had not been present in Scotland meant that the question of abdication need not arise.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] On 4 April 1689 a Convention of the Three Estates of Scotland (sister body to the Parliament of Scotland) declared that James "had acted irregularly" by assuming regal power (government) "without ever taking the Coronation Oath required by Scots Law".
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] Thus, he had "FOREFALTED [forfeited] the Right to the Scots Crown, and the Scots Throne is become vacant".
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] "Scots monarchs derived legitimacy from the Convention of the Estates", later declared a Parliament of Scotland, not God, thus ending the principle of divine right of kings.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] Conflict over control of the kirk between Presbyterians and Episcopalians and William's position as a fellow Calvinist put him in a much stronger position.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] He originally insisted on retaining Episcopacy, and the Committee of the Articles, an unelected body that controlled what legislation Parliament could debate.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] Both would have given the Crown far greater control than in England but he withdrew his demands due to the 1689–1692 Jacobite Rising.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] 2. the Convention of the Estates was a parliament and so parliament could just rewrite it.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] Here is the Claim of Right understood and upheld for its secular constitutional provisions quite as much as for its religious provisions.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] The English succession was provided for by the English Act of Settlement 1701, which ensured that the monarch of England would be a Protestant member of the House of Hanover.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] Until the union of parliaments, the Scottish throne might be inherited by a different successor after Queen Anne, who had said in her first speech to the English parliament that a union was "very necessary".
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] The Scottish Act of Security 1704, however, was passed after the English parliament, without consultation with Scotland, had designated Electoress Sophia of Hanover (granddaughter of James I and VI) as Anne's successor, if Anne died childless.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] The Act of Security granted the Parliament of Scotland, the three Estates, the right to choose a successor and explicitly required a choice different from the English monarch unless the English were to grant free trade and navigation.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] Then the Alien Act 1705 was passed in the English parliament, designating Scots in England as "foreign nationals" and blocking about half of all Scottish trade by boycotting exports to England or its colonies, unless Scotland came back to negotiate a Union.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] To encourage a union, "honours, appointments, pensions and even arrears of pay and other expenses were distributed to clinch support from Scottish peers and MPs".
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] The Scottish economy was severely impacted by privateers during the 1688–1697 Nine Years' War and the 1701 War of the Spanish Succession, with the Royal Navy focusing on protecting English ships.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] This compounded the economic pressure caused by the Darien scheme, and the seven ill years of the 1690s, when 5–15% of the population died of starvation.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] The Scottish Parliament was promised financial assistance, protection for its maritime trade, and an end to economic restrictions on trade with England.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] The votes of the Court party, influenced by Queen Anne's favourite, James Douglas, 2nd Duke of Queensberry, combined with the majority of the Squadrone Volante, were sufficient to ensure passage of the treaty.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] The role played by bribery has long been debated. £20,000 was distributed by David Boyle, 1st Earl of Glasgow, of which 60% went to the Duke of Queensberry, the Queen's Commissioner in Parliament.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] Another negotiator, John Campbell, 2nd Duke of Argyll was given an English dukedom.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] Professor Sir Tom Devine agreed that promises of "favours, sinecures, pensions, offices and straightforward cash bribes became indispensable to secure government majorities".
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] As for representation going forwards, Scotland was, in the new united parliament, only to get 45 MPs, one more than Cornwall, and only 16 (unelected) peers in the House of Lords.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] There were mixed opinions in Scotland about the prospect of a union with England.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] Sir George Lockhart of Carnwath, the only Scottish negotiator to oppose Union, noted "the whole nation appears against (it)".
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] Another negotiator, Sir John Clerk of Penicuik, who was an ardent Unionist, observed it was "contrary to the inclinations of at least three-fourths of the Kingdom".
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] As the seat of the Scottish Parliament, demonstrators in Edinburgh feared the impact of its loss on the local economy.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] Elsewhere, there was widespread concern about the independence of the kirk, and possible tax rises.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] Virtually all of the print discourses of 1699–1706 spoke against incorporating union, creating the conditions for widespread rejection of the treaty in 1706 and 1707.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] In the wake of unionist proselytising in the autumn of 1706 and early 1707, many Scots were undecided about the prospect of a union.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] Rather, there was considerably more support in Scotland for a federal union with England than an incorporative one, similar to the devolved Scottish parliament that would be established within Britain nearly three centuries later.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] As the treaty passed through the Parliament of Scotland, opposition was voiced by petitions from shires, burghs, presbyteries and parishes.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] According to Christopher Whatley, however, calls for a union with England began in Scotland itself in the 1690s for the purpose of safeguarding the law, line of succession, and to improve the economy.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] Ireland, though a kingdom under the same crown, was not included in the union.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] It remained a separate kingdom, unrepresented in Parliament, and was legally subordinate to Great Britain until the Renunciation Act 1783.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] In July 1707 each House of the Parliament of Ireland passed a congratulatory address to Queen Anne, praying that "May God put it in your royal heart to add greater strength and lustre to your crown, by a still more comprehensive Union".
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] The British government did not respond to the invitation and an equal union between Great Britain and Ireland was out of consideration until the 1790s.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] The union with Ireland finally came about on 1 January 1801.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] Deeper political integration had been a key policy of Queen Anne from the time she acceded to the throne in 1702.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] Under the aegis of the Queen and her ministers in both kingdoms, the parliaments of England and Scotland (the **Act for a Treaty with England 1705**) agreed to participate in fresh negotiations for a union treaty in 1705.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] Both countries appointed 31 commissioners to conduct the negotiations.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] Most of the Scottish commissioners favoured union, and about half were government ministers and other officials.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] At the head of the list was the Duke of Queensberry, and the Lord Chancellor of Scotland, the Earl of Seafield.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] The English commissioners included the Lord High Treasurer, Sidney Godolphin, 1st Earl of Godolphin, the Lord Keeper of the Great Seal, William Cowper, Baron Cowper, and a large number of Whigs who supported union.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] Tories were not in favour of union and only one was represented among the commissioners.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] Negotiations between the English and Scottish commissioners took place between 16 April and 22 July 1706 at the Cockpit in London.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] Each side had its own particular concerns.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] After negotiations ended in July 1706, the acts had to be ratified by both Parliaments.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] In Scotland, about 100 of the 227 members of the Parliament of Scotland were supportive of the Court Party.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] For extra votes the pro-court side could rely on about 25 members of the Squadrone Volante, led by the James Graham, 4th Marquess of Montrose and John Ker, 1st Duke of Roxburghe.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] The Court party enjoyed significant funding from England and the Treasury and included many who had accumulated debts following the Darien Disaster.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] The act ratifying the Treaty of Union was finally carried in the Parliament of Scotland by 110 votes to 69 on 16 January 1707, with a number of key amendments.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] News of the ratification and of the amendments was received in Westminster, where the Act was passed quickly through both Houses and received the royal assent on 6 March.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] Though the English Act was later in date, it bore the year '1706' while Scotland's was '1707', as the legal year in England began only on 25 March.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] In Scotland, the Duke of Queensberry was largely responsible for the successful passage of the Union act by the Parliament of Scotland.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] In Scotland, he was greeted by stones and eggs but in England he was cheered for his action.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] He had personally received around half of the funding awarded by the Westminster Treasury.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] In April 1707, he travelled to London to attend celebrations at the royal court, and was greeted by groups of noblemen and gentry lined along the road.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] From Barnet, the route was lined with crowds of cheering people, and once he reached London a huge crowd had formed.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] On 17 April, the Duke was gratefully received by the Queen at Kensington Palace and the Acts came into effect on 1 May 1707.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] A day of thanksgiving was declared in England and Ireland but not in Scotland, where the bells of St Giles rang out the tune of *"why should I be so sad on my wedding day"*.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] The Treaty of Union, agreed between representatives of the Parliament of England and the Parliament of Scotland in 1706, consisted of 25 articles, 15 of which were economic in nature.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] In Scotland, each article was voted on separately and several clauses in articles were delegated to specialised subcommittees.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] Article 1 of the treaty was based on the political principle of an incorporating union and this was secured by a majority of 116 votes to 83 on 4 November 1706.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] To minimise the opposition of the Church of Scotland, an Act was also passed to secure the Presbyterian establishment of the Church, after which the Church stopped its open opposition, although hostility remained at lower levels of the clergy.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] The treaty as a whole was finally ratified on 16 January 1707 by a majority of 110 votes to 69.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] The two Acts incorporated provisions for Scotland to send representative peers from the Peerage of Scotland to sit in the House of Lords.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] It guaranteed that the Church of Scotland would remain the established church in Scotland, that the Court of Session would "remain in all time coming within Scotland", and that Scots law would "remain in the same force as before".
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] Other provisions included the restatement of the Act of Settlement 1701 and the ban on Roman Catholics from taking the throne.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] It also created a customs union and monetary union.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] The Act provided that any "laws and statutes" that were "contrary to or inconsistent with the terms" of the Act would "cease and become void".
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] The Scottish Parliament also passed the Protestant Religion and Presbyterian Church Act 1707 guaranteeing the status of the Presbyterian Church of Scotland.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] The English Parliament passed a similar Act, 6 Ann. c.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] 40—later named the Union with Scotland (Amendment) Act 1707—united the Privy Council of England and Privy Council of Scotland and decentralised Scottish administration by appointing justices of the peace in each shire to carry out administration.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] In effect it took the day-to-day government of Scotland out of the hands of politicians and into those of the College of Justice.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] On 18 December 1707 the Act for better Securing the Duties of East India Goods was passed which extended the monopoly of the East India Company to Scotland.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] In the year following the Union, the Treason Act 1708 abolished the Scottish law of treason and extended the corresponding English law across Great Britain.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] Clark, gaining "freedom of trade with England and the colonies" as well as "a great expansion of markets".
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] The agreement guaranteed the permanent status of the Presbyterian church in Scotland, and the separate system of laws and courts in Scotland.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] However, the Scottish economy was lagging behind not only from the impact of wars, but also because of chronic deflation and industrial underdevelopment.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] Scotland remained a predominantly agrarian society, and the lack of manpower caused by previous conflicts contributed to an underwhelming agricultural output, which intermittently escalated into local food shortages or famines.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] In turn, the overreliance of Scottish landowners on foreign goods led to a deficit of financial capital, as gold and silver were exported overseas and deflation occurred.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] The Scottish Parliament attempted to combat the issue by attracting foreign investment; duty on ship building materials was lifted, taxes on new manufacturing stocks were cut, and customs on textile and linen goods were removed.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] Scotland grew increasingly dependent on its linen industry, which became the biggest source of employment after agriculture and constituted one-third of Scottish industry.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] Continental linen industries could outcompete Scotland, and protectionist tariffs implemented by Scotland led to tariff wars as European countries closed their markets to Scotland.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] In this situation, England became the largest foreign market for Scottish linen; however, while the tariffs in place shielded Scotland from the much larger English industry, England also retaliated against them.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] This forced Scotland to seek economic alternatives.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] At the time, trade with colonies was rapidly growing in importance in Europe, and trade with colonies was very attractive to Scotland, given its pastoral economy.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] American colonies had a high demand of agricultural goods such as leather skins of goats and sheep, which would have provided Scotland a valuable source of income.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] Search for colonial trade, along with the frustration caused by economic and political rivalry with England, led to the Darien scheme – an unsuccessful attempt to establish a Scottish colony in the Gulf of Darién.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] The failure of the Darien scheme led to a financial crisis in Scotland.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] The high cost of its project exacerbated the deflation in Scotland.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] The Bank of Scotland had dangerously low reserves, and in early 1700s a run on the bank occurred, along with temporary suspension of business.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] Ultimately, the Scottish bank managed to stay solvent, although the persisting deflation and low reserves largely contributed to the feeling of Scottish economy being in a precarious position.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] Economist Aida Ramos argues that the Darien scheme could have succeeded if it was to receive support from either England or Spain, and that it lacked the capability to create a threat to England or its interests.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] According to Ramos, the English intervention against the scheme was to meet the expansionary aims of England, as to ensure both its colonial dominance as well as the annexation of Scotland.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] By 1703, the Scottish government was highly disillusioned with the union, and many believed that the only way to let the Scottish economy flourish was to separate from England.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] Scotland would try to establish further autonomy from England with the Act of Security 1704, which provoked a retaliation from England – Scottish ministers were bribed, and Alien Act 1705 was passed.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] According to the Alien Act, unless Scotland appointed commissioners to negotiate for union by Christmas, every Scot in England would be treated as an alien, leading to the confiscation of their English estates.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] Additionally, Scottish wares were to be banned from England.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] The Scottish economy was now facing a crisis, and the parliament was polarised into pro-union and anti-union factions, with the former led by Daniel Defoe.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] The unionists stressed how important trade with England is to the Scottish economy, and seen trade with continental Europe as not beneficial.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] They argued that the Scottish economy could survive by trading with England, and sanctions that would result from the Alien Act would collapse the economy.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] For Defoe, joining the union would not only prevent the Alien Act, but also remove additional limitations and regulations and lead Scotland to prosperity.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] Anti-unionists questioned the English goodwill and criticised the unionist faction for submitting to the English blackmail.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] They argued that Scotland could make a recovery by trading with the Netherlands, Spain and Norway, allowing Scotland to diversify its own industries as well.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] They argued that the union would make Scotland unable to conduct independent trade policy, meaning that any possibility to remove the flaws in Scottish economy would be gone forever, which would turn Scotland into a "mere satellite of the richer kingdom".
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] Ultimately, Scottish ministers voted in favour of the union, despite the lack of public support, with the overwhelming majority of the Scottish population at the time protesting vociferously against any union with England.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] Many Scots considered themselves to have been betrayed by their own elites, and that the union bill was able to pass only thanks to English bribery.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] In the first few decades after the union, England did not end up becoming the main trading partner of Scotland, as other European powers became the primary source of imported goods for Scotland.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] For at least the first 40 years after the union, Scotland persisted in its traditional trade patterns, and the economic situation of Scotland was not as dire as that described in the months leading up to the Acts of Union.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] Christopher Whatley writes, however, that by 1799, it was reported that the union of Scotland with England had not only benefitted the Scottish economy, but promoted a "commercial prosperity" unknown to any people.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/acts-of-union-1707] A commemorative two-pound coin was issued to mark the tercentennial—300th anniversary—of the Union, which occurred two days before the Scottish Parliament general election on 3 May 2007.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/anglo-scottish-border] The **Anglo-Scottish border** is a land boundary that separates the countries of England and Scotland on the island of Great Britain.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/anglo-scottish-border] It runs for 96 miles (154 km) between Marshall Meadows Bay on the east coast and the Solway Firth in the west.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/anglo-scottish-border] The Firth of Forth was the border between the Picto-Gaelic Kingdom of Alba and the Anglian Kingdom of Northumbria in the early 10th century.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/anglo-scottish-border] It became the first Anglo-Scottish border with the annexation of Northumbria by Anglo-Saxon England in the mid-10th century.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/anglo-scottish-border] In 973, the Scottish king Kenneth II attended the English king Edgar the Peaceful at Edgar's council in Chester.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/anglo-scottish-border] After Kenneth had reportedly done homage, Edgar rewarded Kenneth by granting him Lothian.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/anglo-scottish-border] Despite this transaction, the control of Lothian was not finally settled and the region was taken by the Scots at the Battle of Carham in 1018 and the River Tweed became the *de facto* Anglo-Scottish border.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/anglo-scottish-border] The Solway–Tweed line was legally established in 1237 by the Treaty of York between England and Scotland.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/anglo-scottish-border] It remains the border today, with the exception of the Debatable Lands, north of Carlisle, and a small area around Berwick-upon-Tweed, which was taken by England in 1482.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/anglo-scottish-border] Berwick was not fully annexed into England until 1746, by the Wales and Berwick Act 1746.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/anglo-scottish-border] For centuries until the Union of the Crowns, the region on either side of the boundary was a lawless territory suffering from the repeated raids in each direction of the Border Reivers.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/anglo-scottish-border] The age of marriage under Scots law is 16, while it is 18 under English law.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/anglo-scottish-border] The border settlements of Gretna Green to the west, and Coldstream and Lamberton to the east, were convenient for elopers from England who wanted to marry under Scottish laws, and marry without publicity.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/anglo-scottish-border] The land border is near and roughly parallel to the 420 million-year-old Iapetus Suture.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/anglo-scottish-border] This expansion was driven by Norman, Breton, and Flemish forces encouraged by both Norman England and Alba, who dispossessed and colonised lands of Strathclyde, Galloway and Lothian to Northumbria, Cumberland (Cumbria), and Westmorland (Westmoringas).
[src:anglo-scottish-border/anglo-scottish-border] Previously, this broad region had been a complex mosaic of Brythonic, Anglian, Gaelic—including Norse and Norse-Gael communities and polities.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/anglo-scottish-border] The border country, historically known as the Scottish Marches, is the area on either side of the Anglo-Scottish border including parts of the modern council areas of Dumfries and Galloway and the Scottish Borders, and parts of the English counties of Cumbria and Northumberland.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/anglo-scottish-border] It is a hilly area, with the Scottish Southern Uplands to the north, and the Cheviot Hills forming the border between the two countries to the south.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/anglo-scottish-border] In 1333, during the Second War of Scottish Independence, Scotland was defeated at the Battle of Halidon Hill and Edward III occupied much of the borderlands.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/anglo-scottish-border] Edward declared Edward Balliol the new King of Scots, in exchange for much of southern Scotland and absolute supplication, but this was not recognised by the majority of the Scottish nobility who remained loyal to David II and conflict continued.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/anglo-scottish-border] By 1341, Perth and Edinburgh had been retaken by the Scots and Edward Balliol fled to England, effectively nullifying the supposed treaty.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/anglo-scottish-border] Edward would continue the war but would be unable to restore the puppet ruler Balliol to the throne and with the Treaty of Berwick (1357) Scottish independence was once again acknowledged with any pretence to territorial annexations dropped.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/anglo-scottish-border] A 16th-century Act of the Scottish Parliament talks about the chiefs of the border clans, and a late 17th-century statement by the Lord Advocate uses the terms "clan" and "family" interchangeably.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/anglo-scottish-border] Although Lowland aristocrats may have increasingly liked to refer to themselves as "families", the idea that the term "clan" should be used for Highland families alone is a 19th-century convention.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/anglo-scottish-border] This interchangeability, however, is conditional rather than automatic: Agnew and the Lord Lyon's own guidance both state that a clan or family is a legally recognised "noble incorporation" only once it has a chief recognised by the Lord Lyon.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/anglo-scottish-border] A name group without a recognised chief has no equivalent legal standing under either label.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/anglo-scottish-border] For centuries the Marches on either side of the boundary was an area of mixed allegiances, where families or clans switched which country or side they supported as suited their family interests at that time, and lawlessness abounded.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/anglo-scottish-border] Before the personal union of the two kingdoms under James, the border clans would switch allegiance between the Scottish and English crowns depending on what was most favourable for the members of the clan.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/anglo-scottish-border] For a time a powerful local clan dominated a region on the border between England and Scotland.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/anglo-scottish-border] It was known as the Debatable Lands and neither monarch's writ was heeded.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/anglo-scottish-border] Following the 1603 Union of the Crowns, King James VI & I decreed that the Borders should be renamed "the Middle Shires".
[src:anglo-scottish-border/anglo-scottish-border] In the same year the King placed George Home, 1st Earl of Dunbar in charge of the pacification of the borders.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/anglo-scottish-border] Courts were set up in the towns of the Middle Shires and known reivers were arrested.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/anglo-scottish-border] The more troublesome and lower classes were executed without trial; known as "Jeddart justice" (after the town of Jedburgh in Roxburghshire).
[src:anglo-scottish-border/anglo-scottish-border] Mass hanging soon became a common occurrence.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/anglo-scottish-border] In 1605 he established a joint commission of ten members, drawn equally from Scotland and England, to bring law and order to the region.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/anglo-scottish-border] This was aided by statutes in 1606 and 1609, first to repeal hostile laws on both sides of the border, and then to more easily prosecute cross-border raiders.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/anglo-scottish-border] Reivers could no longer escape justice by crossing from England to Scotland or vice versa.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/anglo-scottish-border] The rough-and-ready Border Laws were abolished and the folk of the middle shires found they had to obey the law of the land like all other subjects.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/anglo-scottish-border] In 1607 James felt he could boast that "the Middle Shires" had "become the navel or umbilic of both kingdoms, planted and peopled with civility and riches".
[src:anglo-scottish-border/anglo-scottish-border] After ten years King James had succeeded; the Middle Shires had been brought under central law and order.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/anglo-scottish-border] By the early 1620s the Borders were so peaceful that the Crown was able to scale down its operations.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/anglo-scottish-border] Despite these improvements, the Joint Commission continued its work, and as late as 25 September 1641 under King Charles I, Sir Richard Graham, a local laird and English MP, was petitioning the Parliament of Scotland "for regulating the disorders in the borders".
[src:anglo-scottish-border/anglo-scottish-border] Conditions along the border generally deteriorated during the Commonwealth and Protectorate periods, with the development of Moss-trooper raiders.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/anglo-scottish-border] Following the Restoration, ongoing border lawlessness was dealt with by reviving former legislation, renewed continually in eleven subsequent acts, for periods ranging from five to eleven years, up until the late 1750s.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/anglo-scottish-border] The Debatable Lands lay between Scotland and England to the north of Carlisle, the largest population centre being Canonbie.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/anglo-scottish-border] For over three hundred years the area was effectively controlled by local clans, such as the Armstrongs, who successfully resisted any attempt by the Scottish or English governments to impose their authority.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/anglo-scottish-border] In 1552 commissioners met to divide the land in two: Douglas of Drumlanrigg leading the Scots; Lord Wharton leading the English; the French ambassador acting as umpire.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/anglo-scottish-border] The Scots' Dike was built as the new frontier, with stones set up bearing the arms of England and of Scotland.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/anglo-scottish-border] Berwick is famous for its hesitation over whether it is part of Scotland or England.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/anglo-scottish-border] Berwickshire is in Scotland while the town is in England, although both Berwick and the lands up to the Firth of Forth belonged to the Kingdom of Northumbria in the Early Middle Ages.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/anglo-scottish-border] The town changed hands more than a dozen times before being finally taken by the English in 1482, though confusion continued for centuries.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/anglo-scottish-border] The Wales and Berwick Act 1746 clarified the status of Berwick as an English town.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/anglo-scottish-border] In the 1950s the artist Wendy Wood moved the border signs south to the middle of the River Tweed as a protest.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/anglo-scottish-border] In 2008 SNP MSP Christine Grahame made calls in the Scottish Parliament for Berwick to become part of Scotland again.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/anglo-scottish-border] At the River Tweed the border runs down the middle of the river, however between the villages of Wark and Cornhill the Scottish border comes south of the river to enclose a small riverside meadow of approximately 2 to 3 acres (about a hectare).
[src:anglo-scottish-border/anglo-scottish-border] It is said locally that every year the men of Coldstream (to the North of the river) would play mob football with the men of Wark (to the South of the river) at Ba, and the winning side would claim the Ba Green for their country.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/anglo-scottish-border] As Coldstream grew to have a larger population than Wark, the Coldstream men always defeated the Wark men at the game, and so the land became a permanent part of Scotland.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/anglo-scottish-border] It is a common misconception that Hadrian's Wall marks the Anglo-Scottish border.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/anglo-scottish-border] The wall lies entirely within England and has never formed this boundary.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/anglo-scottish-border] While in the west, at Bowness-on-Solway, it is less than 0.6 mi (1.0 km) south of the border with Scotland, in the east it is as much as 68 miles (109 km) away.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/anglo-scottish-border] For centuries the wall was the boundary between the Roman province of *Britannia* (to the south) and the Celtic lands of *Caledonia* (to the north).
[src:anglo-scottish-border/anglo-scottish-border] However *Britannia* occasionally extended as far north as the later Antonine Wall.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/anglo-scottish-border] Furthermore, to speak of England and Scotland at any time prior to the ninth century is anachronistic; such nations had no meaningful existence during the period of Roman rule.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/anglo-scottish-border] "Hadrian's Wall" is nonetheless sometimes used as an informal reference to the modern border, often semi-humorously.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/anglo-scottish-border] Cumbria and Northumberland have among the largest Scottish-born communities in the world outside Scotland.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/anglo-scottish-border] 16,628 Scottish-born people were residing in Cumbria in 2001 (3.41% of the county's population) and 11,435 Scottish-born people were residing in Northumberland (3.72% of the county's population); the overall percentage of Scottish-born people in England is 1.62%.
[src:anglo-scottish-border/anglo-scottish-border] Consequently, almost 9% of Scotland's population is English-born (459,486), with higher than average percentages of English-born people in both Dumfries & Galloway and the Scottish Borders council areas, respectively, reaching as high as 35% or higher English-born.
